Total F16 decode GPU time: ~10.2 ms/tok. Histogram had this at ~17 ms/tok (inclusive nesting inflated it ~70%).

Recoverable headroom toward 190 GiB/s ceiling: ~6.4 ms/tok = ~10% of decode wall = +1.5 t/s if perfect, realistically +1 t/s.

Concrete kernel targets (ranked by recoverable wall):

1. 4096x1024 wave-per-row + N-element unroll. Currently single-block-per-row LDS kernel (256 threads/row, in_dim/256=16 elements per thread) at 95 GiB/s. Port the Q8_0 wave-per-row pattern (1 wavefront per row, __shfl_down reduction) but each lane processes N consecutive F16 elements per loop iteration to amortize loop overhead — the naive 1-elem-per-lane port already exists as dead code (rocm_matmul_f16_wave_4_kernel, rocm_matmul_f16_wave_8_kernel) but regressed at 1 elem/iter. Try N=8 or N=16.

2. 16384x24 k-split. n_rows=24 means 24 wavefronts at <1/CU occupancy. Split in_dim=16384 into K chunks (e.g. K=8, chunk=2048), launch 24*K=192 wavefronts that atomicAdd partial sums to a zero'd output. ROCM_DEFINE_MATMUL_F16_KSPLIT(2048) already exists as dead code from prior session — wire it for this shape.

3. 4096x256 wave-per-row + N-element unroll. 83 calls/tok x 32us = 2.62 ms/tok. Same approach as #1.

4. 4096x512 same approach. 1.87 ms/tok at 82 GiB/s.

All shapes are below ceiling but moderately so — these are not 'serial-on-1-thread' wins like router_select was. Expect +1.5 t/s as a soft ceiling for the bundle.

Validation:
